  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Sending Off Sa-mi on His Journey Home to the Southern State
  author: Gwon Min-su
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Today I watch you depart beyond the city gates,
    Your form freed from the tumult and confusion of the world.
    I seek out the highest pavilion by the river,
    And there I linger—a traveler in the summer heat.

    The gains and losses of this world know no end,
    Yet how many springs remain in the halls at home?
    I too wish to return, yet cannot go,
    And cannot bear the frequent visits of my clearest dreams.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Sa-mi (士美) appears to be the courtesy name of the traveler being seen off. The poem reflects both the speaker's farewell to a departing friend and a deeper longing for home and rest that remains unfulfilled.
